findings.message:
AbstractCouponStrategy + PercentageCouponStrategy + FixedCouponStrategy + CouponHandlerFactory is four things (three files worth of ceremony) for what is, right now, a lookup table. The pattern adds no capability — every new coupon type still requires editing this exact file. Replace the whole structure with a data table and one function:

```ts
const COUPONS: Record<string, { kind: 'percent' | 'flat'; value: number }> = {
  WELCOME10: { kind: 'percent', value: 0.10 },
  FIVEOFF:   { kind: 'flat',    value: 500  },
  // ...
};
export function applyCoupon(amount: number, code: string | undefined): number {
  if (!code) return amount;
  const c = COUPONS[code];
  if (!c) return amount;
  return c.kind === 'percent' ? Math.floor(amount * (1 - c.value)) : amount - c.value;
}
```

When the rules genuinely get complex (date-bound, customer-specific) you'll know what shape the abstraction needs — you don't know yet.
